Misc 2: control in nominal context, inanim control? (one could argue that there has to be someone who uses opera to torture etc. But cf. "Diese Stücke haben den Zweck, die Sängerinnen eines nach dem anderen zu quälen")

According to Colomo (2011, p. 201 f.), directive "lassen" is a control verb and allows either object ("A:N") or implicit ("-:N") control. I suspect that what we see here is an instance of implicit control where the controler is additionaly indicated in a PP (according to SB, this happens sometimes).
